data.chText: （身体上的）伤，伤口；（武器造成的）伤
data.enText: an injury to part of the body, especially one in which a hole is made in the skin using a weapon

data.chText: 腿伤、头伤等
枪伤；刀伤；枪伤；刺伤
战争中的旧伤
护士清洗了伤口。
伤口愈合得很慢。
他由于胸部受伤而死亡。
data.enText: He died from the wounds he had received to his chest.

data.chText: （心灵上的）伤，创伤
data.enText: mental or emotional pain caused by sth unpleasant that has been said or done to you

data.chText: 激烈争吵之后的感情创伤需要一些时间才能愈合。
data.enText: After a serious argument, it can take some time for the wounds to heal.

data.chText: 再次见到他打开了旧的创伤。
data.enText: Seeing him again opened up old wounds .

data.chText: （失败或失望后）恢复元气，重整旗鼓
data.enText: to spend time trying to get your strength or confidence back after a defeat or disappointment

data.chText: 揭旧疮疤
data.enText: to remind sb of sth unpleasant that happened or existed in the past

data.chText: 在伤口上抹盐；使雪上加霜
data.enText: to make a difficult experience even more difficult for sb

data.chText: 使（身体）受伤；（用武器）伤害
data.enText: to injure part of the body, especially by making a hole in the skin using a weapon

data.chText: 他的手臂受过伤。
data.enText: He had been wounded in the arm.

data.chText: 使（心灵）受伤；伤感情
他那刻薄的话语使她感到深受伤害。
data.enText: She felt deeply wounded by his cruel remarks.

data.text: injure ♦ wound ♦ hurt ♦ bruise ♦ maim ♦ sprain ♦ pull ♦ twist ♦ strain

data.chText: 以上各词主要指在事故中伤害、使受伤。
data.enText: These words all mean to harm yourself or sb else physically, especially in an accident.

data.chText: 尤指在事故中伤害、使受伤：
data.enText: to harm yourself or sb else physically, especially in an accident

data.chText: 他打曲棍球时膝盖受了伤。
data.enText: He injured his knee playing hockey.

data.chText: 撞车事故中有三人受伤。
data.enText: Three people were injured in the crash.

data.chText: 指使身体受伤，尤指用武器伤害：
data.enText: [often passive] ( rather formal ) to injure part of the body, especially by making a hole in the skin using a weapon

data.chText: 这次袭击中有50人受重伤。
data.enText: 50 people were seriously wounded in the attack.

data.chText: wound常指在战争中或在波及许多人的其他袭击中受伤。
data.enText: Wound is often used to talk about people being hurt in war or in other attacks which affect a lot of people.

data.chText: 指（使）疼痛、受伤：
data.enText: to cause physical pain to sb/yourself; to injure sb/yourself

data.chText: 你伤着自己了吗？
用hurt还是injure？
在事故中身体受伤可用hurt或injure，hurt强调引起的身体疼痛，injure强调身体部位受到某种程度的损伤。
data.enText: You can hurt or injure a part of the body in an accident. Hurt emphasizes the physical pain caused; injure emphasizes that the part of the body has been damaged in some way.

data.chText: 指摔伤、撞伤、（使）出现淤伤
data.enText: to make a blue, brown or purple mark (= a bruise) appear on the skin after sb has fallen or been hit; to develop a bruise

data.chText: 指使残废、使受重伤
data.enText: ( rather formal ) to injure sb seriously, causing permanent damage to their body

data.chText: 扭伤（踝、腕、膝）
data.enText: to injure part of your body, especially your ankle, wrist or knee, by suddenly bending it in an awkward way, causing pain and swelling

data.chText: 拉伤，扭伤（肌肉等）
data.enText: to damage a muscle, etc., by using too much force

data.chText: 扭伤（踝、腕、膝）
data.enText: to suddenly bend a part of your body, especially your ankle, wrist or knee, in an awkward way, causing an injury that involves pain and swelling

data.chText: 用sprain还是twist？
sprain作名词表示踝、腕、膝扭伤引起疼痛或肿胀，作动词表示使踝、腕、膝扭伤；twist作动词表示扭伤踝、腕、膝。
data.enText: A sprain is an injury to your ankle, wrist or knee that causes pain and swelling; to sprain your ankle/wrist/knee is to injure it in this way. To twist your ankle/wrist/knee is to do the action (= to suddenly bend it in an awkward way) that causes the injury.

data.chText: 指损伤、拉伤、扭伤：
data.enText: to injure yourself or part of your body by making it work too hard

data.chText: 别在光线差的地方看书把眼睛给伤了。
data.enText: Don't strain your eyes by reading in poor light.

ex.chText: 在那场足球赛中，我的腿受了重伤。
ex.enText: I hurt my leg badly in the football match.

ex.chText: 她不是故意要伤害你的感情。
ex.enText: She didn't mean to hurt your feelings.

synonyms.bx: 普通用词，指肉体上受到伤害时，其程度弱于 injure 和 wound；也可指精神、感情方面受到伤害。

ex.chText: 汽车翻倒，他的双腿受伤了。
ex.enText: The car was turned over and his legs were injured.

ex.chText: 在一次事故中，3名工人严重受伤。
ex.enText: Three workers were critically injured in an accident.

synonyms.bx: 比 hurt 正式，主要指在意外事故中受伤。

ex.enText: The robber wounded him with a knife.

synonyms.bx: 指用刀、枪等伤害某人，也可指使人在精神上受到伤害。

data.enText: to spend time trying to get your strength or confidence back after a defeat or disappointment

data.chText: 揭旧疮疤
data.enText: to remind sb of sth unpleasant that happened or existed in the past

data.chText: 在伤口上抹盐；使雪上加霜
data.enText: to make a difficult experience even more difficult for sb

tr: the act of inflicting a wound
a casualty to military personnel resulting from combat
a figurative injury (to your feelings or pride)
example: he feared that mentioning it might reopen the wound
deep in her breast lives the silent wound
The right reader of a good poem can tell the moment it strikes him that he has taken an immortal wound--that he will never get over it"--Robert Fros

tr: an injury to living tissue (especially an injury involving a cut or break in the skin)
cause injuries or bodily harm to

example: She hurt me when she did not include me among her guests
This remark really bruised my ego

value.def: Wound is the past tense and past participle of wind 2 .
A wound is damage to part of your body, especially a cut or a hole in your flesh, which is caused by a gun, knife, or other weapon.

example.ex: Six soldiers are reported to have died from their wounds.
example.tran: 据报道，有6名士兵因伤而亡。

value.tran: (刀、枪或其他武器所致的)创伤，伤口

value.def: If a weapon or something sharp wounds you, it damages your body.

example.ex: A bomb exploded in a hotel, killing six people and wounding another five...
example.tran: 一枚炸弹在一家旅馆爆炸，造成6人死亡，5人受伤。

example.ex: The driver of an evacuation bus was wounded by shrapnel...
example.tran: 一辆疏散大巴的司机被弹片炸伤。

example.ex: The two wounded men were taken to a nearby hospital.
example.tran: 两名受伤男子被送到附近医院。

posc.def: The wounded are people who are wounded.

example.ex: Hospitals said they could not cope with the wounded...
example.tran: 医院表示无力收治这么多伤者。

example.ex: They were told to carry their wounded and leave their dead.
example.tran: 他们被命令抬走伤员，丢下死者。

value.tran: （武器或其他利器）伤害，使受伤

value.def: A wound is a lasting bad effect on someone's mind or feelings caused by a very upsetting experience.

example.ex: She has been so deeply hurt it may take forever for the wounds to heal.
example.tran: 她内心受伤太深，也许再也无法愈合。

value.def: If you are wounded by what someone says or does, your feelings are deeply hurt.

example.ex: He was deeply wounded by the treachery of close aides...
example.tran: 他被亲密助手的背叛深深地伤害了。

example.ex: My children have wounded me in the past.
example.tran: 我的孩子们过去曾伤害过我。

example.ex: I think she feels desperately wounded and unloved.
example.tran: 我想她觉得受到了莫大的伤害，无人爱她。

value.boxu_tran: 注意，表示某人受到意外伤害，如路遇车祸或进行体育运动时受伤，不能用 wound, 而要用 injure 或 injury：A man and his baby were injured in the explosion (一名男子和他的小孩在爆炸中受伤)，Many of the deaths that occur in cycling are due to head injuries (骑自行车时发生的死亡事故很多都是由于头部受伤所致)。在较为正式的英语中，injury 也可作不可数名词：Two teenagers escaped serious injury when their car rolled down an embankment (两个少年在汽车滚下堤岸后侥幸没有受重伤)。wound 通常仅限于指士兵在战场上受伤，或指因蓄意实施的暴力行为而受伤：stab wounds (刺伤)。
value.boxu_usage: Note that when someone is hurt accidentally, for example, in a car crash or when they are playing sport, you do not use the word wound. You use injure and injury instead. A man and his baby were injured in the explosion... Many of the deaths that occur in cycling are due to head injuries. In more formal English, injury can also be an uncount noun. Two teenagers escaped serious injury when their car rolled down an embankment. Wound is normally restricted to soldiers who are injured in battle, or to deliberate acts of violence against a particular person. ...stab wounds.

value.def: If you say that someone is licking their wounds, you mean that they are recovering after being defeated or made to feel ashamed or unhappy.

example.ex: The British team was returning home yesterday to lick its wounds after defeat by India.
example.tran: 英国队负于印度队后，昨日回国休整。

value.tran: （失败或被羞辱后）舔伤，重整旗鼓

value.def: Something that opens old wounds or reopens old wounds reminds someone about an upsetting experience in the past which they would prefer to forget.

example.ex: Courts have been reluctant to reopen old wounds by trying crimes that are decades old.
example.tran: 法院不愿重揭旧伤疤，去审理几十年前的罪案。

value.tran: 揭旧伤疤(指重提他人不愿提起的痛苦往事)
